## üçåBanana Split (Advanced):

Ready to stretch your creativity? Advanced examples push beyond simple tools to create more sophisticated solutions that address complex educational challenges.

It can take some experience to know whether an idea is at this level. Before getting started, consider these key questions about your app concept:

* What is the app used to do?  
* What do you want the app to look like?  
* How should the user click, drag, or type into the app? How should the app respond?  
* What should the app store for the user or save? If you are entering data into the app, you want to save it somewhere so that you don't have to re-enter it each time you run it. We recommend using localStorage, which allows data to persist in your browser between sessions.  
* Does your app require any use of AI? If so, you'll need an API key from a large language model provider (OpenAI, Gemini, or Claude). Be sure to request a field where you can input this key when creating your app.

An app moves into the advanced category when it involves sophisticated data processing or connects multiple systems. As noted in the Medium examples, complex data processing can challenge even the best AI models. You know your app idea might be at the advanced level if:

* Your app needs to access or display data stored externally. If you have a Google Sheet with your data, but you want your app to display that information somewhere that is not that Google Sheet‚Ä¶that adds an additional level of complication.  
* You need different platforms to communicate with each other. "I want to make something that gets data from Powerschool into a Google Sheet." This requires you use something called an Application Programming Interface \- it is a set of rules and requirements that let one program talk to another.  
* Your app needs to optimize or find ideal arrangements based on multiple criteria. Needing to create a duty schedule or room assignments for students from information submitted via Google form‚Ä¶that's a challenging problem for both humans and computers. This will take some experience and time to get right, and large language models can struggle with this just like we humans do. It is possible, and Evan has experience doing this, but it is likely more than a task for a thirty minute build session. 

## Prompt Structure

This is how you might put together your own prompt to get one of the large language models to build your app.

I want to make a tool that \[ describe what it does here\]

I want it to look like: \[  describe it in words, or upload a drawing of what you want it to look like  \]

When I \[   describe how you click, drag, type, or move things on the screen     \]

If you need more information from me, please ask me questions one at a time.

\[If you need AI functionality, include the following:

Include a place where I can paste my API key for the large language model I want to use. Here is sample code from my chatbot showing how to create code that uses this model:

\]

Please make me a single HTML page with code that I can paste into an editor. I want to be able to load the page in a web browser any time I want to use it, even when I am not online.

## What is ‚ÄúVibe Coding‚Äù?

The term ‚Äúvibe coding‚Äù was coined by experienced AI expert Andrej Karpathy in February, 2025\. The idea for the term is that you aren‚Äôt actually doing coding at all. Instead, you are clearly describing what you want an AI agent to build, and then it builds and codes it for you. You don‚Äôt actually touch the code or paste anything yourself \- you simply give verbal feedback for what is or is not working, and ask the AI agent to fix it.

##  Vibe Coding Option \#2: Lovable.dev 

You can get to the site at [https://lovable.dev/](https://lovable.dev/).  
![][image13]  
Before you get started, here are some things to keep in mind:

* This site really can build some sophisticated things for you on its own. It also lets you put the tool online at a URL that can be easily shared with other people.   
* The free version gives you five requests to the AI agent to build your idea per day. Each request can accomplish quite a bit, so I encourage you to fill each request with clear details about the most important things you want the app to do, how the user might interact with it, and what appears on the screen. The more detail you give for what is in your head, the less you leave to chance.

It can take some experience knowing what to put in these prompts, but the general requirements are pretty simple. You want to do some thinking about your answers to these questions.

* What is the app used to do?  
* How should the user click, drag, or type into the app? How should the app respond?  
* What should the app store for the user or save? If you are entering data into the app, you want to save it somewhere so that you don‚Äôt have to re-enter it each time you run it.  I usually recommend something called localStorage for this because it stays in the browser you use to run it.  
* What data does it need to share with other users or other websites?  
* Does your app require any use of AI? You will need to have something called an API key for one of the large language models (from OpenAI, Gemini, or Claude) to do this.

If you need to save data so that it is accessible to others online, that gets more complicated. You will need to tell the app to save the data in a database or a spreadsheet. Since this might involve student data or data that belongs to your school, you should get someone who understands the issues related to online data (a tech facilitator or member of the IT/Tech support department) to help you. 

## Vibe Coding Example: Diamond Challenge

My colleague who teaches Entrepreneurship asked if I could build him an app to give his students guidance in submitting proposals to the Diamond Challenge entrepreneurship competition.

Here is an example of what I gave it in the first prompt \- this is complex, just so you can see what it can do: 

‚ÄúI want to make an AI active website for anyone to use that helps them do applications to the Diamond entrepreneurship challenge. This is the document as a Google Doc: 

\<\<Pasted in the content of the Diamond Entrepreneurship Challenge application \- omitted for brevity\>\>

‚ÄúFor each input, I want the person to be able to type or paste in their answers. The current content should be saved to localStorage. A wand button by each input field, when clicked, should submit the entire document with entered information to an API endpoint, and then give feedback for the field linked to that input in the context of the entire document. Let's use Google Gemini API with a field for an API key.‚Äù

Lovable was able to put together this website all on its own:

Pretty cool, for sure. I needed to tell it to use a different Google AI model, to show the feedback in formatted HTML, but other than that, it worked pretty well.
